---
import { Picture } from 'astro:assets';
import darkroom from '../assets/darkroom.png';
import workbench from '../assets/workbench.png';
import lighttable from '../assets/lighttable.png';
import studio from '../assets/studio.png';
---

<section class="ritual" id="ritual">
  <div class="ritual-header">
    <div class="section-label reveal">The Ritual</div>
    <h2 class="section-heading center reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Film. Light. Paper. Retouch.</h2>
    <p class="section-body reveal" style="margin: 0 auto; --reveal-delay: 160ms">
      Four stages, in the order you actually make a photograph. Source,
      interpretation, realization, mend.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="ritual-stages">

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage One · Origin</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Film</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">Choose where the photograph comes from.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          Start in Pure RAW, your file exactly as the camera saw it, or in
          Origin, Latent's own blend. Then put it through emulsion: thirty-seven
          film stocks, five chemistries (C-41, ECN-2, E-6, K-14, B&amp;W), five
          scanners. The negative develops, the enlarger prints, the paper holds
          the image. Halation, grain physics, push and pull, and a latitude
          indicator that reads off the stock you picked.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <Picture
          src={darkroom}
          formats={['avif', 'webp']}
          widths={[480, 800, 1200, 1600]}
          sizes="(min-width: 900px) 800px, 100vw"
          alt="Film stage, stocks, chemistry, scanner, paper"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage Two · Interpret</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Light</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">Bring the image forward.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          Exposure, the four lights (Highlights, Shadows, Whites, Blacks), and
          a tone curve with L, R, G, B channels and a live histogram. Then
          Structure: Depth for how forms separate, Surface for the texture of
          skin and stone and fabric. Then Dye Density, four sliders that handle
          color the way film does (Intensity, Retention, Separation, Purity),
          never one flat saturation knob. And finally Color, an eight-channel
          densitometer plate over a rainbow strip. None of it as zones, all of
          it as one field.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <Picture
          src={workbench}
          formats={['avif', 'webp']}
          widths={[480, 800, 1200, 1600]}
          sizes="(min-width: 900px) 800px, 100vw"
          alt="Light stage, tone, dye density, color spectrum"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage Three · Realize</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Paper</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">Finish on a surface.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          The Enlarger sets paper grade, contrast, and density. The Paper brings
          its own base and finish, with control over how the print settles into
          its blacks. The Wash is a split-tone that warms or cools shadows,
          midtones, and highlights on their own, a real darkroom toner. The
          Fall-Off burns light at the edges of the frame the way an enlarger
          naturally would. Texture lays a plate of real film grain (35mm, 16mm,
          500T, 8mm) across the print. A Gallery Finish frame, if you want one.
          Then Deliver, Quick Export, or Export Catalogue for the whole batch.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <Picture
          src={lighttable}
          formats={['avif', 'webp']}
          widths={[480, 800, 1200, 1600]}
          sizes="(min-width: 900px) 800px, 100vw"
          alt="Paper stage, enlarger, wash, fall-off, finish"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage Four · Mend</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Retouch</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">The polishing pass.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          Spotting brush, clone stroke, the work you'd normally leave the app to
          do. After the print is realized, this is where you lift the dust, tidy
          the small distractions, and get the photograph ready.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <Picture
          src={studio}
          formats={['avif', 'webp']}
          widths={[480, 800, 1200, 1600]}
          sizes="(min-width: 900px) 800px, 100vw"
          alt="Retouch stage, spotting and clone"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

